likeness without their permission.

It isn't a copyright violation if I publish Game 3 of the 1972 world
championship, but if I say it's &quot;Fischer-Spassky&quot; then most of the
publication value would extend from the knowledge of who played the game,
and when.

Oddly, copyright protection might slow the computer onslaught a bit, as
theory would take longer to proliferate and thus reward original thinkers
far more, especially if they publish their innovations.

